{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585337"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:09:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:09:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14959"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14959"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.67,0.13,0.09,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7647"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64327"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7647"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14959"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49759"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6798"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"8109"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18704"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18707"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64327"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely to cause atypical pneumonia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Staphylococcus aureus","Mycoplasma pneumoniae","Klebsiella pneumoniae","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Haemophilus influenzae"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAtypical pneumonia, also known as \u0027walking pneumonia\u0027, typically presents with a gradual onset of symptoms including fatigue, headache, and low-grade fever. The respiratory symptoms are often less prominent than in typical bacterial pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe classic causes of atypical pneumonia include \u003Cstrong\u003EMycoplasma pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E, Chlamydophila pneumoniae, and Legionella pneumophila. These organisms produce a clinical picture distinct from typical bacterial pneumonia caused by organisms like \u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EKlebsiella pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E is particularly common in young adults and often occurs in community outbreaks. It lacks a cell wall, making it resistant to beta-lactam antibiotics. The infection typically causes a gradual onset of symptoms with prominent constitutional symptoms (fatigue, headache) and less severe respiratory symptoms compared to typical bacterial pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mycoplasma pneumoniae is a common cause of atypical pneumonia, particularly in young adults.","Atypical pneumonia presents with gradual onset and predominantly non-respiratory symptoms.","Mycoplasma pneumoniae lacks a cell wall and cannot be treated with beta-lactam antibiotics."],"references":["Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical microbiology. JP Medical Ltd","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Vaughn VM, Dickson RP, Horowitz JK, Flanders SA. Community-Acquired Pneumonia: A Review. JAMA. 2024 Oct 15;332(15):1282-1295. doi: 10.1001/jama.2024.14796. PMID: 39283629","Miyashita N. Atypical pneumonia: Pathophysiology, diagnosis, and treatment. Respir Investig. 2022 Jan;60(1):56-67. doi: 10.1016/j.resinv.2021.09.009. Epub 2021 Nov 5. PMID: 34750083."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49759"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14959"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49759"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T12:27:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T12:28:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7647"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64327"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description